*****************************************************************************

@node Intro "1. Introduction"
AXsh is a shell-environment designed to allow remote users connect
to your machine without fear of abuse such as formatting your hard
disks.  AXsh deals with the protection issue by only allowing the
users to run commands they are authorized to run and only access
files they are allowed to access.

AXsh is a stand-alone package, but it can also be run under UUCP or
almost any other package, but you need to do some changes to some
of the configuration files.

AXsh consists of four main parts:  the AXsh shell, AX-sysghost,
which holds information about users, AX-server, which takes
incoming calls and starts AXsh sessions and the executables written
for AXsh.

You need:
	- KS2.0 or newer (OR arp.library v39)
	- C= Installer to use the 2.0 install script

To use network or file transfer:
	- xprzmodem.library 2.52 or newer
	- any other xprotocol library

@{fg highlight}WARNING!@{fg text}
@{bg highlight}	The program icons that come in this package don't
	work with ks1.3 !  For example the AXsh icon which starts
	an AXsh session will certainly crash your ks1.3-machine.
	@{bg background}

@endnode

*****************************************************************************

@node Installation "2. Installing AXsh system"

With 1.32 installation script you can do in-place installation.
AXsh is installed into the directory you unpacked the archive.
It is still possible to install AXsh anywhere you like. Just
follow the instructions in the installation script.

The installer will ask you to select the right drawer and files to
install.  If you want to neatly install AXsh to its own directory,
you should create a subdirectory.  The install script will place
every one of the AXsh directories to the directory you select and
won't create its own AXsh directory.  This is because I want the
install script to be able to do the installation into a hard disk
partition also.

The new >2.0 installation script is quite intelligent and it will
allow you to install AXsh into a partition, into a directory or on
top of an old version.  And s:user-startup will be updated
accordingly.

@{fg highlight}
	Do NOT just delete this manual after you have read this,
	because this file is not automatically copied to the AXsh
	directories.@{fg text}
@endnode

*****************************************************************************

@node HandInstall "2.1 Installing by hand"
Create a new directory or a partition for AXsh and make an assign
to point to that directory:
	@{b}assign AXsh: <AXsh directory>@{ub}

Or if you rather dedicate a whole partition to AXsh, it's
reasonable to label it `AXsh':
	@{b}relabel <partition name> AXsh@{ub}

Next unpack the InstallDisk packet to the AXsh directory:
	@{b}lha x InstallDisk AXsh:@{ub}

This will take a while to be executed.  After the shell prompt
appears again, you should have all files unpacked.  You should
@{"customize" link Missing} the configuration to fully use AXsh's cababilities.
Now, try this from any CLI or shell:
	@{b}path AXsh:bin/
	AXsh -con@{ub}

AXsh version string and login prompt should appear.  Give login
name @{b}root@{ub} and password @{b}root@{ub}.  Now you should notice if you
have succeeded in the first part of the installation process.
Use "exit" to terminate an @{"AXsh session" link Shell.guide/Main}.

If you want to use AXsh remotely, you have to make NEWAUX:
available:
	@{b}mount NEWAUX: from AXsh:etc/Mountlist.AXsh@{ub}

Now NEWAUX:  is added to the system and it is ready to handle the
builtin serial line.  If you want to use a different serial device,
refer to the manual pages for ax-server and newaux-handler.  You
can now start the AX-server with "AX-server".  The server will not
by default answer the calls, but you can use it to launch new
console sessions.  See @{"/etc/rc.server" link rc.server} to see how to configure
the AX-server.

Next thing to do is to make the starting and mounting automatic.

@{fg highlight}AmigaOS 2.0 installation:@{fg text}

Edit s:user-startup using your favourite text editor and write:
	@{b}assign AXsh: <AXsh directory>
	mount NEWAUX: from AXsh:etc/Mountlist.AXsh@{ub}

After that, save the user-startup and open the AXsh installation
diskette's Storage directory from Workbench.  You'll see icons with
an A on the top left corner.  Move these icons to your boot disc's
WBStartup directory.  Now, when system opens Workbench, it
automatically launches these programs.  If you're not using
Workbench, follow the AmigaOS 1.3 installation steps, but edit
s:user-startup instead of s:startup-sequence.  If you are using a
partition labeled "AXsh" for the AXsh system, you should of course
leave out the assign command.

@{fg highlight}AmigaOS 2.1 installation:@{fg text}

In addition to the AmigaOS 2.0 installation steps move the NEWAUX
handler from the AXsh installation diskette's Storage/DOSDrivers
directory to the system Devs/DOSDrivers directory and leave out the
mount command from the user-startup.  You should also copy the
catalog files from bin/Catalogs to AXsh:bin/Catalogs, if you want
to use other languages than the default English.

Currently AXsh (the shell itself), Mail and Ami (private mail
programs), Rn (news reader) and FFE (file frontend) all support
WB2.1 locale.library.  Included languages are:

English   Default (Included in the programs)
suomi	  (Finnish)	by Pasi Ojala		albert@cs.tut.fi
fran軋is  (French)	by Cedric Beust		Cedric.Beust@sophia.inria.fr
dansk	  (Danish)	by Soeren Berg Hansen	siera@imada.ou.dk
espal	  (Spanish)	by Sebastian Delmont	sdelmont@dino.conicit.ve
svenska	  (Swedish)	by Morgan Ericsson	morgan@krynn.augs.se
deutsch   (German)      by Mirko Thiesen and ｫvarious othersｻ

Thousand thanks and happy and productive future to all translators.
If you are willing to do translation to your own language, just
contact me.

@{fg highlight}AmigaOS 1.3 installation:@{fg text}

Edit s:startup-sequence using your favourite text editor and write
before the "endcli >nil:" command:
	@{b}assign AXsh: <AXsh directory>
	execute AXsh:etc/Startupadd.AXsh@{ub}

And that's it.  Save the modified startup-sequence and try booting
the machine.  You may check the Startupadd.AXsh file to see what is
done there.

@endnode

*****************************************************************************

@node Online "3. Getting Online"
You have many choices on how to handle the incoming calls, but
whichever method you choose, the basic principle is that @{"NEWAUX:" link Newaux-handler}
will do the actual work between AXsh and the serial port. AXsh
and all the programs that are run from it just use AmigaDOS
standard input/output provided by NEWAUX:.  This also means that
almost any program that uses standard input/output can be used
under AXsh, provided that it is otherwise safe, i.e. a user can't
do any harm with the command.

3.1 @{"AX-server" link AX-server}
3.2 @{"Getty" link Getty}
3.3 @{"Trapdoor" link Trapdoor}
3.4 @{"Other" link Other}

Also, take a look into the /info/InOtherSystems directory, where I
have added several files that are relevant when using AXsh as a
door or with other software.

@endnode

*****************************************************************************

@node AX-server "3.1 AX-server"
AX-server is the program provided with the AXsh package that
answers the calls and starts AXsh sessions to the serial line when
a connection is established.

AX-server has its own configuration file called @{"/etc/rc.server" link rc.server}.
It contains modem initialization commands, event definitions and
command lines that are used to initiate new AXsh sessions.

@endnode

*****************************************************************************

@node rc.server "/etc/rc.server"
Default AX-server configuration file looks like this:

	%bpslock:
	19200
	%bps:
	19200
	%serverpri:
	1
	%starthour:
	0
	%stophour:
	25
	%newshell:
	newshell newaux:%d/%u/shared/checkcd/useodu from AXsh:etc/remote-startup
	%newcon:
	newshell raw:0/9/428/210/AXsh/CLOSE from AXsh:etc/local-startup
	%modem-reset:
	ATZ
	%modem-aa:
	ATS25=255W2\N3&C1&D0M0E0S0=1
	%eventhour:
	25
	%eventmins:
	0
	%eventnumber:
	ATX4E0DT161320
	%eventcommand:
	AXsh:bin/nntpnews <newaux: >newaux:
	%ringflash:
	0
	%device:
	serial.device
	%unitnumber:
	0
	%handshake:
	cts/rts

In the first line %bpslock:  defines possible baud rate lock.  If
you have a high speed modem that can always use the same speed
(e.g.  19200 bps), you can define %bpslock:.  If AX-server finds a
%bpslock:  specifier from the configuration file, it uses ALWAYS
that bps rate regardless of actual connection bps rate.  It will
still show the connect message received from the modem in the title
bar.
	@{fg highlight}If your modem can't use locked speed, REMOVE the
	entry totally, leaving the next line blank won't be enough!@{fg text}

For now you should only use speeds that are available in serial
preferences !  If you are using multiple devices or other than the
builtin serial port, you MUST use a fixed DTE-speed and also tell
newaux:  what the used speed is (for example
NEWAUX:serial.device/6/shared/checkcd/speed38400).

If %bpslock:  is not used (i.e.  the entry is missing), %bps:
defines the highest possible speed of you modem.  All the
controlling commands ("ATZ" etc.) are sent at this baud rate.  Baud
rate between the modem and the Amiga is changed to match the rate
in the phone line after a successful connection.  The baud rate in
preferences is set accordingly so that NEWAUX will operate at the
right speed.  This is why you can only use speeds that are possible
in serial preferences.

%serverpri:  defines AX-server's priority.  It should be less than
five.  AX-server does not hog the CPU, so the priority is only to
keep the responses nice and quick.  It may take a while if the
modem is giving it a hard time by using the handshake (7-WIRE) to
hold the transmission.  In this case you might want to hard-reset
the modem.

If you are running a system that only accepts calls at night or
only at daytime, you can define the starting and stopping hours for
AX-server.  %starthour:  defines the hour when AX-server starts to
answer the calls and %stophour:  when it stops.  For example if
your system opens at 20:00 (08:00 PM) and closes down at 06:00
(06:00 AM) you type here:

	%starthour:
	20
	%stophour:
	06

%newshell:  opens a new AXsh by executing a script which usually is
stored in AXsh:etc/ directory and named remote-startup.  This opens
an AXsh session for external users.  If you are using a fixed DTE
speed that is not available in preferences, you need to add e.g.
/speed57600 to the NEWAUX:  string.  This entry shows how the
launching of AXsh sessions are done in other environments also.

Local console session is opened in the same way.  %newcon:  opens a
window to the console and then executes AXsh starting script.  You
can change the window parameters, but don't touch the
AXsh:etc/local-startup file.  It's just fine.  The window should be
80 columns wide, because currently most programs expects that.  If
necassary, add some overscan to make the window larger (I have
724x564 in PAL-interlace).

%modem-reset:  defines the string that resets the modem.  Usually
ATZ.  It is wise to store modem settings with echo disabled, as
that saves you from some unexpected difficulties.  You should also
disable the DTR checking, because there is delay between AX-server
releasing the serial and NEWAUX:  opening it again.  You can also
set the DTR delay to a high enough value.  If you don't want to do
it that way, you can try the @{"other" link Online} methods available and just
drop AX-server completely.

%modem-aa:  defines the autoanswer string.  This string is sent to
the modem when the time is between starthour and stophour.  You may
have to modify this depending on your modem's command language.
When AX-server goes to sleep, it just resets the modem.

%eventhour:  and %eventmins:  tells AX-server when to make a
network call.  %eventnumber:  defines the string that AX-server
sends to modem when an event time occurs.  Usually it contains
ATDT<phonenumber>.

%eventcommand:  defines the script or program that is to be
executed after a connection is established between your machine and
remote hub.  If the number is busy or the connect fails, AX-server
will try again in five or ten minutes until it succeeds or the the
event hour does not match anymore.  If you are calling an AXsh hub,
the event command would be something like:

	@{b}AXsh:bin/net <newaux: >newaux:@{ub}

AX-server can be made to flash the screen when phone rings.
%ringflash:  defines the situations when it flashes the screen:

	0 - do not flash
	1 - when sleeping (not taking calls in)
	2 - when answering calls
	3 - always

There are also two additional definitions.  You can use %device:
and %unitnum:  to use some other device than the built-in serial.
If you set these, you have to do modifications to the %newshell:
too.  e.g.

	@{b}NEWAUX:modem0.device/0/shared/checkcd/useodu@{ub}

However, the ring checking is still done directly from the CIA.  If
you use a printer much, you might want to turn the flash off,
because the modem Ring Indicator uses the same CIA input line with
the printer Online Select line and AX-server would think that the
phone is ringing.

	@{fg highlight}If you are not using the builtin serial, you
	should have 0 in the %ringflash: entry !@{fg text}

%handshake:  configuration entry is for those people who don't have
the possibility to use cts/rts (7wire) handshaking with their
modem.  In that case set it to "none".  NEWAUX:  uses handshaking
by default, so you also need to change the %newshell:  entry to
include /noflow.

	@{b}NEWAUX:modem0.device/0/noflow/shared/checkcd/useodu@{ub}

You can also use several different configuration files, because one
can be picked using a command line parameter when invoking
AX-server.  The name of the configuration file can be seen in the
window title bar during the setup.  The syntax is:

	@{b}AX-server [-f<config-file>] [-x<xpos>] [-y<ypos>] [-h<title-height>]@{ub}

As you can see, it is also possible to define where the window will
be opened.  AX-server is "System title font"-adaptive.  You still
should remember that if the window will not fit into the screen,
the program does not try to reopen it and exits.


You can also run a multiline system, newaux-handler should be able
to handle several connection at one.  However, if it does not work
with your multiserial card, you can mount one handler per each
line, named differently of course.  You also need as many server
configurations.  You can also use the old AXAUX-handler, but you
need seperate mounted handler for each line, because AXAUX-handler
is not designed to handle several ports simultaneously.

Since AXsh 1.31 you can also use 'variables' in the %newshell: entry.
	%d	Devicename
	%u	Unitnumber
	%s	Connect speed

@endnode

*****************************************************************************

@node Getty "3.2 Getty"
You can use Getty (or variants) to launch AXsh sessions also.
However, you need a dummy account for UUCP, or an entry for each
user that explicitly starts AXsh @{"for that user" link
Shell.guide/OPTIONS}.

Passwd entry for UUCP:
	@{b}bbs,*,444,0,(BBS-login),ram:,execute axsh:etc/UUCP-startup2.0@{ub}

UUCP-startup2.0:
	@{b}stack 20000
	AXsh:bin/AXsh <>newaux:serial.device/0/shared/checkcd/useodu -log
	quit@{ub}

@endnode

